{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17533294","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17533294"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:34:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:34:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14777"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14777","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14777"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.68,0.21,0.07,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7468"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103019"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7468","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7468"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14777"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85484"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"3572"},{"type":"tags","id":"4632"},{"type":"tags","id":"5587"},{"type":"tags","id":"5588"},{"type":"tags","id":"5611"},{"type":"tags","id":"5623"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18279"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36334"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103019","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103019"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman is undergoing laparoscopic cholecystectomy under general anaesthesia. She has a medical history of myocardial infarction two years ago and hypertension. Her medications include metoprolol, aspirin, ramipril, and atorvastatin. Induction of general anaesthesia is uncomplicated, with a standard propofol and fentanyl induction followed by propofol infusion for maintenance. Ten minutes into the procedure following insufflation of the abdomen and the formation of the port sites, her heart rate suddenly drops from 75/min to 42/min. Her blood pressure has fallen from 130/80 mmHg to 85/50 mmHg. Her SpO2 is 99%, end-tidal CO2 38 mmHg, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of the bradycardia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blood loss","Vagal stimulation","Propofol toxicity","Beta blocker effect","Myocardial ischaemia"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute bradycardia and hypotension during laparoscopic cholecystectomy. Despite multiple potential contributing factors, the timing of the bradycardia coinciding with peritoneal insufflation strongly suggests \u003Cstrong\u003Evagal stimulation\u003C/strong\u003E as the primary cause. The vagus nerve provides parasympathetic innervation to the heart, and peritoneal stretch from pneumoperitoneum can trigger an intense vagal response leading to bradycardia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeta blocker effect\u003C/strong\u003E may be contributing to the bradycardia given the patient\u0027s regular metoprolol use. However, the sudden onset coinciding with insufflation makes this less likely to be the primary cause, as beta blocker-induced bradycardia typically has a more gradual onset and likely would have been noted pre-operatively if the patient had taken their regular medication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood loss\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes tachycardia and hypotension rather than bradycardia. Whilst initial entry into the abdominal cavity is a high-risk time for inadvertent vascular injury, the time course and nature of the presentation would suggest peritoneal stretch as the cause of the haemodynamic changes. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMyocardial ischaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is an important consideration given the patient\u0027s cardiac history. However, the temporal relationship with insufflation makes vagal stimulation more likely as the primary cause. Continuous ECG monitoring would be important to exclude this.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPropofol toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E can cause bradycardia and hypotension, but this would be more likely to occur during induction or with an inadvertent bolus. The timing of changes coinciding with insufflation makes this a less likely cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement should include temporarily reducing insufflation pressures, and if necessary, administration of anticholinergic medication such as atropine or glycopyrrolate. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Multiple factors can contribute to intraoperative bradycardia including vagal stimulation, beta blockade, and severe blood loss.","The combination of bradycardia and hypotension should prompt consideration of hypovolaemia or cardiac causes.","Timing and context of intraoperative cardiovascular changes help determine the most likely cause."],"references":["Heyba M, Khalil A, Elkenany Y. Severe Intraoperative Bradycardia during Laparoscopic Cholecystectomy due to Rapid Peritoneal Insufflation. Case Rep Anesthesiol. 2020 Jun 6;2020:8828914. doi: 10.1155/2020/8828914. PMID: 32566315; PMCID: PMC7294365.","Cheung CC, Martyn A, Campbell N, Frost S, Gilbert K, Michota F, Seal D, Ghali W, Khan NA. Predictors of intraoperative hypotension and bradycardia. Am J Med. 2015 May;128(5):532-8. doi: 10.1016/j.amjmed.2014.11.030. Epub 2014 Dec 22. PMID: 25541033.","Atkinson, Tamara M. Giraud, George D. Togioka, Brandon M. Jones, Daniel B. Cigarroa, Joaquin E. Cardiovascular and Ventilatory Consequences of Laparoscopic Surgery 2017 J Circulation, p700-710, V135, N7, doi:10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.116.023262."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85484"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14777"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85484","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85484"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-18T14:17:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-18T14:17:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7468"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103019"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCo